                  </persName>
             (Police-constable H 88). On the day stated, I saw the prisoner go into a house in Wentworth-street; he hung this coat across a chair-back; I went in, and asked him who it belonged to - he said to Mr. Sheen, who was there asleep; I awoke him, and asked if it was his - he said, "No, I know nothing about it."</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320705-293-person2386">
                  ANN 
                  SHEEN
               <interp inst="t18320705-293-person2386" type="surname" value="SHEEN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320705-293-person2386" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320705-293-person2386" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the daughter of 
               <persName id="t18320705-293-person2387">
                  William 
                  Sheen
               <interp inst="t18320705-293-person2387" type="surname" value="Sheen"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320705-293-person2387" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320705-293-person2387" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , of Wentworth-street. I was cleaning the door between twelve and one o'clock; the prisoner brought in this coat; the officer came in and took him away? - I never saw him before, I swear that; the door was open and he came in- my father is a wheelright; he was asleep on a table, as he had been out all night on a job.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. They do know me, and her brother has been tried here. Witness. He may say so, but I never saw him in my life before.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. My mother is dead, and my father has three of us to keep; these people buy things, and I went there to sell it.</p>
